<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="163" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[136,1452,1400,2075]" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,713,1508,1534]" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Distribution in Santa Maria river basin:—</emphasis>
Three species were found, i.e. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lehmann 1826: 17) D. M. Porter (1964: 211)" authorityName="D. M. Porter" authorityPageNumber="211" authorityYear="1964" baseAuthorityName="Lehmann" baseAuthorityPageNumber="17" baseAuthorityYear="1826" class="Demospongiae" family="Acarnidae" genus="Wigginsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="langsdorffii">
<emphasis box="[1073,1326,1509,1535]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Wigginsia langsdorffii</emphasis>
(Lehmann 1826: 17) D.M. 
<bibRefCitation author="Porter, D. M." box="[302,513,1544,1571]" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" pagination="210 - 211" refId="ref9525" refString="Porter, D. M. (1964) A New Name for Malacocarpus. Taxon 13 (6): 210 - 211. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 1216611" type="journal article" year="1964">Porter (1964: 211)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[527,616,1545,1571]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[136,229,1610,1632]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,279,1582]" captionTargetId="figure-58@10.[302,1286,275,1586]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. A) Opuntia megapotamica (orange flowers). B) Parodia arnostiana (yellow flowers). C) P. herteri (pink flowers). D) P. linkii (yellow flower). E) P. mammulosa (yellow flower). F) P. nothorauschii. G) P. ottonis(flores yellow flower). H) P. ritteriana(yellow flower). I) P. tenuycilindrica. J) Wigginsiasellowii (yellow flower). K) W. langsdorffii (pale-yellow flower). L) W. turbinata (yellow flower). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Fig. 3K</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authority="(Link &amp; Otto 1827: 425) F. Ritter (1979: 196)" authorityName="F. Ritter" authorityPageNumber="196" authorityYear="1979" baseAuthorityName="Link &amp; Otto" baseAuthorityPageNumber="425" baseAuthorityYear="1827" box="[636,1263,1544,1571]" class="Demospongiae" family="Acarnidae" genus="Wigginsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="sellowii">
<emphasis box="[636,757,1545,1571]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">W. sellowii</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Link, J. H. &amp; Otto, C. F." box="[770,1029,1544,1571]" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" pagination="24 - 420" refId="ref8897" refString="Link, J. H. &amp; Otto, C. F. (1827) Gattung Echinocactus. Verein zur Beforderung des Gartenbaues in den Preussischen Staaten 3: 24 - 420." type="journal article" year="1827">Link &amp; Otto 1827: 425</bibRefCitation>
) F. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ritter, F." box="[1061,1263,1544,1571]" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" refId="ref9733" refString="Ritter, F. (1979) Kakteen in Sudamerika. Band 1. Brasilien / Uruguay / Paraguay. Friedrich Ritter Selbstverlag, Spangenberg, 374 pp." type="book" year="1979">Ritter (1979: 196)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1278,1357,1545,1571]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[136,229,1610,1632]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,279,1582]" captionTargetId="figure-58@10.[302,1286,275,1586]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. A) Opuntia megapotamica (orange flowers). B) Parodia arnostiana (yellow flowers). C) P. herteri (pink flowers). D) P. linkii (yellow flower). E) P. mammulosa (yellow flower). F) P. nothorauschii. G) P. ottonis(flores yellow flower). H) P. ritteriana(yellow flower). I) P. tenuycilindrica. J) Wigginsiasellowii (yellow flower). K) W. langsdorffii (pale-yellow flower). L) W. turbinata (yellow flower). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Fig. 3J</figureCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Arechavaletae 1905: 235) D. M. Porter (1964: 211)" authorityName="D. M. Porter" authorityPageNumber="211" authorityYear="1964" baseAuthorityName="Arechavaletae" baseAuthorityPageNumber="235" baseAuthorityYear="1905" class="Demospongiae" family="Acarnidae" genus="Wigginsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="turbinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">W. turbinata</emphasis>
(Arechavaletae 1905: 235) D.M. 
<bibRefCitation author="Porter, D. M." box="[604,815,1580,1607]" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" pagination="210 - 211" refId="ref9525" refString="Porter, D. M. (1964) A New Name for Malacocarpus. Taxon 13 (6): 210 - 211. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 1216611" type="journal article" year="1964">Porter (1964: 211)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[830,915,1581,1607]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[136,229,1610,1632]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,279,1582]" captionTargetId="figure-58@10.[302,1286,275,1586]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. A) Opuntia megapotamica (orange flowers). B) Parodia arnostiana (yellow flowers). C) P. herteri (pink flowers). D) P. linkii (yellow flower). E) P. mammulosa (yellow flower). F) P. nothorauschii. G) P. ottonis(flores yellow flower). H) P. ritteriana(yellow flower). I) P. tenuycilindrica. J) Wigginsiasellowii (yellow flower). K) W. langsdorffii (pale-yellow flower). L) W. turbinata (yellow flower). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Fig. 3L</figureCitation>
), associated with rocky outcrops and saxicolous vegetation. They are plants of globular to cylindrical habit of 
<quantity box="[833,954,1616,1643]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.6" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" unit="cm" value="13.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="6.0">6 to 20 cm</quantity>
in diameter, densely tomentose in the apex, with tuberculated ribs, bell-shaped yellow flowers approximately 
<quantity box="[874,929,1652,1679]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" unit="cm" value="5.0">5 cm</quantity>
in length, fruits (glabrous) pink or red, hidden by the tom, devoid of trichomes or bristles. Depending on the species, flowering begins in October–December, bearing fruit soon after.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[136,1452,1400,2075]" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">
In the SMRB all species found are endemic to the Pampa (
<tableCitation box="[856,943,1761,1787]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="5.[136,224,989,1013]" captionText="TABLE 2: Geographic distribution of species found in SMRB in relation to phytophysiognomy, geomorphology and conservation status. Phytophysiognomy: G = Grasslands; SV = Saxicolous vegetation; F = Forest, W = Wetlands. Geomorphology: VH = Volcanic Hills; SH = Sandstone Hills. Conservation Status: EN = Endangered; CR = Critically Endangered; VU = Vunerable; NT = Near Threatened; LC = Least Concern; DD = Deficient Data; NE = Not Evaluated." pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Table 2</tableCitation>
) except for four that are also common to the Atlantic forest. Species of restricted distribution are 
<taxonomicName box="[746,944,1797,1823]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Frailea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="albifusca">
<emphasis box="[746,944,1797,1823]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Frailea albifusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buining &amp; Brederoo" authorityYear="1973" box="[961,1062,1797,1823]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Frailea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lepida">
<emphasis box="[961,1062,1797,1823]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">F. lepida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buining &amp; Brederoo" authorityYear="1972" box="[1079,1238,1797,1823]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Frailea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mammifera">
<emphasis box="[1079,1238,1797,1823]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">F. mammifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. Pontes, A. S. Oliveira &amp; Deble" authorityYear="2018" box="[1255,1445,1797,1823]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Frailea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="erythracantha">
<emphasis box="[1255,1445,1797,1823]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">F. erythracantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hofacker" authorityYear="1988" baseAuthorityName="Lisal &amp; Kolarik" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[136,354,1833,1859]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Parodia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arnostiana">
<emphasis box="[136,354,1833,1859]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Parodia arnostiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="D. R. Hunt" authorityYear="1997" baseAuthorityName="F. Ritter" baseAuthorityYear="1979" box="[368,513,1833,1858]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Parodia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="curvispina">
<emphasis box="[368,513,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">P. curvispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. S. Oliveira &amp; R. Pontes" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Lisal &amp; Kolarik" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[574,708,1833,1858]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Parodia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ritteriana">
<emphasis box="[574,708,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">P. ritteriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which have populations located only in sedimentary and volcanic outcrops, respectively, within the study region, which proves the need for conservation and a management plan for the species’ occurrence areas.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[136,1452,1400,2075]" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">
The floristic diversity of the family is intrinsically related to the edaphic and climatic conditions provided by the stony springs in the Santa Maria River Basin, which constitute a favorable microclimate of intense luminosity, heat and humidity so that species adapted to xeromorphy such as 
<taxonomicName box="[768,881,2013,2039]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Cactaceae</taxonomicName>
develop in this region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[136,1452,1400,2075]" lastBlockId="10.[136,1451,158,221]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="163" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Regarding the populations found, it is noted that there is a lack of knowledge about the conservation of species, especially when there is mining in their areas of occurrence, it has been found in the literature that of the 29 species occurring in SMRB, 9 species are critically endangered. (CR), 9 endangered (EN) and 6 are vulnerable (VU).</paragraph>
